<TITLE>Detroit Regional Transportation Authority makes early 13 5 million debt payment that will save taxpayers</TITLE>
<TEXT>
12 01 a m Updated Operating losses for the seventh consecutive year to near break even EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY 1 29 AT NOON The Detroit Regional Convention Facility Authority narrowed its operational loss for the seventh consecutive year in 2016 after paying down 13 5 million in taxable bonds a move it says will save taxpayers about 11 7 million over the life of the bond issue or 7 75 million in present value dollars The early payment represented more than half of the higher interest 23 5 million taxable bond issue owed on the original 295 35 million in bonds taken out in November 2014 said Patrick Bero CEO and COO of the authority which has operational oversight for Detroit s Cobo Center It was made in addition to a scheduled principal payment of just over 7 million paid last October Next year the authority plans to pay off the remainder of the taxable bond issue and then dip into the tax exempt debt owed Bero said The early payment leaves the authority owing a total of just under 274 8 million Bero said due at various points between now and 2039 The authority continued to operate at a loss last year but narrowed its deficit to 280 166 earnings before interest depreciation and amortization net of debt and operating subsidies The authority and Cobo management company SNG have narrowed the losses for seven consecutive years since taking on oversight of the convention center In 2015 it posted a 2 7 million loss and 3 4 million loss the year before The city was losing an estimated 21 million year on Cobo Center the authority said when it took over control in September 2009 under an agreement between the Michigan State Legislature the City of Detroit and Wayne Oakland and Macomb counties Bero said the authority is approaching a break even point operationally nearly seven years before the 2023 deadline the state legislature set as the last year it will receive subsidies to help fund Cobo s operation He credits the recent renovation and subsequent increase in bookings with helping the events venue turn things around The authority completed a 279 million renovation and upgrade to Cobo Center on time and within budget in August 2015 Among other things the upgrades created a 30 000 square foot atrium with views of the Detroit River and Canada increased parking and improved traffic flow upgraded infrastructure enclosed loading docks and redeveloped the former Cobo Arena as a 40 000 square foot grand ballroom Additionally the authority said a 2 million technology upgrade was completed in mid December to allow 32 000 simultaneous users on Cobo s Wi Fi network In 2016 the event center hosted 16 city wide conventions including the annual North American International Auto Show Cobo lays claim to being the 17th largest convention center in the country with 723 000 square feet of exhibition space and nearly 1 5 million visitors each year 
